    <td valign="top" class="AdminText"><img src="../Images/messageicon.gif" width="15" height="15"><span class="AdminText">Posted 
      on: 11-04-2001 at 09:59:44 
      CET&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;  </span><br>
      <hr>
<b>Errol's view of a Guild (the narrow paternal approach) ;o) </b><br><br>Guilds need structure. Guilds need Leadership. And Guilds needs a goal, something to strive for.<br><br>Without that, "helping eachother" quickly grows stale, as members focus on powerlevelling, getting fancy gear and wants to Raid the Planes.<br><br>If the Guild does not support these simple developments AS WELL as being able to maintain a common sense of "unity", surrounding a charter and a set of guidelines, the point of the guild is moot. Then you might as well call it a "loot group" and be done with it...<br><br>When the Guild grows, the familiar strings keeping people together dissolve and if the guild doesn't grow, you will have one heckuva time going anywhere up-scale.<br><br>Make your decisions known and decide what you as a Leader wants. Do not fool yourself into believing its gonna be a democracy either, it will never be. You have the final say and if people will not respect that, your guild will quickly dissolve. State that from the beginning, so people know what to expect.<br><br>Between the Guilds goals and structure, the leadership and the personal desires of its members, you are the one who stays focused. Make your vision and strategy clear from the beginning. Choose your officers wisely and use them as sparring partners as much as you can, to help you make decisions. Good Officers are invaluable. You can't do everything yourself.<br><br>Members. Always pay strict attention to your members, as they are the reason you made the Guild in the first place. Make it a fun and challenging place to be. You are there for the members, NOT the other way around. Never forget that simple fact. Stay neutral and stay fair. Never take sides if at all possible. Although it can be darn tricky sometimes...<br><br>Its a balance, and a lot of hard work - but its worth it.<br><br>'ere endeth the lesson....<br><br>I wish you all the luck in the world Armanella. I am not saying my views are the only ones who work - its just my way. My reflections from running this guild for almost 2 years. (whoa!).<br><br>Should you ever want some constructive feedback, drop me a mail or a tell. I'll be there.<br><br><br><b>Errol Flynn</b><br>Pathfinder of Tunares Mercy<br><br><i>"That wasn't a bad pull...it was a CHALLENGING pull"</i>
