    <td width="120" valign="top" class="AdminText">Avi<br>
</td>
    <td valign="top" class="AdminText"><img src="../Images/messageicon.gif" width="15" height="15"><span class="AdminText">Posted 
      on: 11-04-2001 at 20:00:53 
      CET&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;  </span><br>
      <hr>
A guild also needs an identity. Without it, a guild is nothing more than a collection of people running around wiht a common guild tag. The Order of Truth is one of the older guilds on the server now, they still exist today. Only reason I know they are still around is because they were the first guild I had ever joined, before leaving to form my beloved Hand of Truth. Why did I leave? They had no identity. Why are they still around today? Because enough alts that haven't been played in monthsstill carry the guild tag.<br><br>When a group of people lose their identity, they cease to exist. This is true of RL as well. When any nation, or ethnic culture loses its individuality and identity, they cease to exist. This has happened hundreds of times throughout history in RL. Entire cultures have simply vanished because they lost what was theirs. Most Americans don't understand the ethnic wars that rock Europe constantly. These are people fighting to maintain their identity, not allowing their culture to go the way so many have in the past.<br><br>Many guilds in EQ have gone the same way. As a guild, you have to know what you stand for, even if it is standing for simple social issues, or raiding. And you have to stick to your identity as that guild. For better or for worse. Take Unity of Twelve as prime example.<br><br>As a guild you make your bed and lay in it so to speak. You create your charter, you have certain ideals, roleplay or not, and you follow them. But when you lose sight of these, and allow too much change to take place, the guild often loses itself amd ceases to be. Then oyu have Unity of Twelve, ripping itself apart, or you have one of the countless mindless, purposeless, taking up space guilds that exist today.<br><br>Change is good, but there must be a constant, an underlying identity that remains throughout. Otherwise you will have to ask yourself <i>"Who are we?"</i>. And by the time you have to ask that question, it will most likely be too late. And remember, identity is not synonomous with ideal... and identity is often times much more the cherished of the two. Ideals come and go with the perspective (just realize that the person playing AVi sid that, not Avi himself).<br><br>Enjoy!<br><br>Neal/Avi/Korach
	<br>
    </td>
